TY  - JOUR
AU  - Britten-Jones, Mark
AU  - Schaefer, Stephen M.
T1  -  Non-Linear Value-at-Risk *
PY  - 1999
Y1  - 1999/01/01
DO  - 10.1023/A:1009779322802
JO  - Review of Finance
JA  - Rev Financ
VL  - 2
IS  - 2
SP  - 161
EP  - 187
SN  - 1572-3097
AB  - Value-at-risk methods which employ a linear (“delta only”) approximation to the relation between instrument values and the underlying risk factors are unlikely to be robust when applied to portfolios containing non-linear contracts such as options. The most widely used alternative to the delta-only approach involves revaluing each contract for a large number of simulated values of the underlying factors. In this paper we explore an alternative approach which uses a quadratic approximation to the relation between asset values and the risk factors. This method (i) is likely to be better adapted than the linear method to the problem of assessing risk in portfolios containing non-linear assets, (ii) is less computationally intensive than simulation using full-revaluation and (iii) in common with the delta-only method, operates at the level of portfolio characteristics (deltas and gammas) rather than individual instruments.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1023/A:1009779322802
ER  - 



